    0x502C + 0x8    = 0x5034
    0x502C - 0x30   = 0x4FFC
    0x502C + 64     = 0x502C + 0x40 = 0x506C
    0x50DA - 0x502C = 0xAE

2.1.2 covers the concept of word size, and 2.1.3 presents the typical sizes of
C data types in modern PCs—I’m already quite familiar with this as well.

2.1.4 discusses addressing and byte ordering (endianness). I implemented a
little‑endian / big‑endian detector in csapp/etc/endian_checker.c.

Interestingly, the terms 'big endian' and 'little endian' come from Jonathan
Swift’s Gulliver’s Travels, where two warring factions could not agree on which
end—the big end or the little end—to break a soft‑boiled egg. These terms were
first used in the context of byte ordering by Danny Cohen.

2.1.5 explains how C stores strings.

'One neat detail: you can generate an ASCII table with man ascii.'

2.1.6 briefly touches on machine code for programs (just a little).
2.1.7 gives a mathematical explanation of Boolean algebra and rings.

