learn CSAPP
read 1.x
Tue Jul 9, 2026
15:53

Actually, I skimmed through CSAPP roughly before, but, you know, reading it
that superficially doesn't really make anything stick deeply in your brain.
So, this time I plan to read this 'bible' thoroughly.

Section 1.1 mentions an interesting fact: 'Infomation is bits + context.'

The book uses the word 'context,' which sounds pretty facny and techy, making
it hard for beginner to grasp. Simply put, context is the current state of the
computer, or to put it even more bluntly, it's 'the way you interpret a string
of bits.'

For example, suppose there is a value '0111 1000' stored in the computer's
memory. Without context, this value is meaningless---it's just a random
combination of bits! But once you associate it with context, things change;
if we treat it as an ASCII value, it represents the lowercase letter 'x'; if we
treat it as an 8-bit unsigned integer, it represents the integer 120.

So, in computers, only 'bits + context' can constitute meaningful 'information'!

The first chapter of the entire CSAPP is a simple tour of computer architecture
(with no labs or assignments). I'm already thoroughly familiar with it, so I
just skipped straight to Chapter 2.

