learn SICP
exercise 1.1 - 1.8
Tue Jul 7, 2026
14:00

Today, I started working on the exercises for SICP Section 1.1.

* First up is Exercise 1.1, which is a very basic introductory problem.

  Interestingly, entering (= 1 1) into my current interpreter returns #t for
  true (as opposed to #f for false).

* Then I tackled Exercise 1.2 (./sicp/p/1_2.scm), which is also quite simple.

  Note that 4/5 cannot be written directly as 0.8; according to the official
  SICP answers, it must be expressed as the combination (/ 4 5).

* Next came Exercise 1.3 (./sicp/p/1_3.scm). I needed to define a procedure
  that takes three numbers and returns the sum of the squares of the two larger
  numbers.

  A clever shortcut here is to sum the squares of all three numbers and then
  subtract the square of the smallest one.

* Exercise 1.4 asks to describe the behavior of a specific procedure.

  This function simply adds the absolute value of b to a.

  The key lies in this ingenious expression: (if (> b 0) + -).

  If b > 0, it evaluates to +, which becomes the operator for the outer
  combination; otherwise, it evaluates to -.

* Exercise 1.5 is really interesting. Ben Bitdiddle wrote a program to detect
  whether an interpreter uses applicative-order or normal-order evaluation:

    (define (p) (p))

    (define (test x y)
      (if (= x 0)
          0
          y))

    (test 0 (p))

  Under applicative-order evaluation, where all arguments are evaluated first,
  this program will loop infinitely.

  Because p is an infinite tail-recursive function, (test 0 (p)) must evaluate
  (p) before proceeding.

  Under normal-order evaluation, arguments are only evaluated when needed. The
  expression first expands to: (if (= 0 0) 0 (p)).

  Note that under both evaluation orders, 'if' follows a special rule: it
  evaluates the predicate first (= 0 0), and then evaluates the consequent
  based on the result.

  Since (= 0 0) is true, it returns 0 and never evaluates (p).

* Exercise 1.6 is also fascinating. Alyssa P. Hacker used 'cond' to define a
  new version of 'if' called 'new-if'.

  The critical difference is that 'new-if' is a regular procedure, whereas 'if'
  is a special form.

  As noted before, 'if' evaluates the predicate first, but 'new-if' lacks this
  short-circuiting behavior.

  Consequently, 'new-if' follows applicative-order evaluation and evaluates
  all its arguments before application, disrupting the intended order of
  execution.

  When using 'new-if' to compute square roots, the program keeps recursively
  calling 'sqrt-iter' even after 'good-enough?' becomes true, eventually
  triggering a stack overflow.

  In fact, 'new-if' never terminates.

* Exercise 1.7 required explaining why the book's implementation of
  'good-enough?' fails for extremely small and extremely large numbers:

    (define (good-enough? guess x)
      (< (abs (- (square guess) x)) 0.001))

  Simply put, this is due to the limited precision of floating-point numbers
  in computers.

  Breaking it down: If we calculate (sqrt 0.00001), the answer should be
  around 0.01.

  However, using 'good-enough?' with a fixed tolerance of 0.001 stops the
  iteration around 0.03, which introduces a massive relative error.

  For extremely large numbers, floating-point representations have a limited
  number of bits, meaning the precision of the mantissa is insufficient at
  large scales.

  The difference between successive guesses will always remain larger than
  0.001, trapping the program in an infinite loop.

  To fix this, I implemented an alternative strategy for 'good-enough?' based
  on how much the guess changes relative to the previous one. I saved this
  algorithm in ./sicp/p/1_7.scm.

* Finally, Exercise 1.8 required implementing Newton's method for computing
  cube roots.

  I successfully implemented this algorithm in ./sicp/p/1_8.scm.

